AIM: 
To write a C program to perform string operations (copy, reverse, concatenate) using 
menu-driven approach. 
  
ALGORITHM: 
1. Start the program. 
2. Display menu: 
 a. String Copy 
 b. String Reverse 
 c. String Concatenate 
 d. Exit 
3. Read the user’s choice. 
4. Perform the operation based on choice: 
Copy: Use strcpy() to copy one string to another. 
Reverse: Reverse string manually. 
Concatenate: Use strcat() to append one string to another. 
5. Repeat menu until user chooses exit. 
6. Stop the program. 
 
PROGRAM: 
#include <stdio.h> 
#include <string.h> 
#include <stdlib.h> 
int main() { 
char str1[100], str2[100], result[100]; 
int choice, i, len; 
while (1) { 
printf("\n--- String Operations Menu ---\n"); 
printf("1. String Copy\n"); 
printf("2. String Reverse\n"); 
printf("3. String Concatenate\n"); 
printf("4. Exit\n"); 
printf("Enter your choice: "); 
scanf("%d", &choice); 
getchar(); // to clear newline from buffer 
switch (choice) { 
case 1: 
printf("Enter a string: "); 
gets(str1); 
strcpy(result, str1); 
printf("Copied string: %s\n", result); 
break; 
case 2: 
printf("Enter a string: "); 
gets(str1); 
len = strlen(str1); 
for (i = 0; i < len; i++) { 
result[i] = str1[len - i - 1]; 
} 
result[len] = '\0'; 
printf("Reversed string: %s\n", result); 
break; 
case 3: 
printf("Enter first string: "); 
gets(str1); 
printf("Enter second string: "); 
gets(str2); 
strcpy(result, str1); 
strcat(result, str2); 
printf("Concatenated string: %s\n", result); 
break; 
case 4: 
printf("Exiting program...\n"); 
exit(0); 
default: 
printf("Invalid choice! Please try again.\n"); 
} 
} 
return 0; 
} 

